  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Provision of Education in Emergencies and Emergency alternative care support for separated and unaccompanied children to  affected IDP girls and boys in Salah Al Din Governorate</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The proposed initiative will support access to quality formal education for 1440 girls and boys, ages 6-17, residing in newly liberated areas, in particularly East Shirqat. This targeting is based on current humanitarian needs, and shall be adjusted for appropriateness should this be required by changes in the humanitarian situation. Education activities will address the protection risks faced by conflict-affected children, particularly those that are out of school, including early marriage, child labour and recruitment of armed children, through the rehabilitation of damaged classrooms identification and mobilization of community members with previous teaching experience and distribution of appropriate emergency education teaching and learning materials. Registered children and youth will receive student kits with appropriate learning materials, and Save the Children (SC) will work with education authorities to coordinate the provision of text books. SC will also train and provide t teachers kits. In order to support child protection and well-being, teachers will receive integrated trainings on psychological first aid (PFA), child safeguarding (CSG), and child protection in emergencies (CPiE). Teachers will also receive emergency education training, on topics including psychological first aid, psychosocial support, child-centered, protective and interactive methodologies, and classroom management, etc., using the Interagency Network for Education in Emergencies (INEE)&#x2019;s Teachers in Crisis Contexts (TICC) training package. SC will conduct targeted and comprehensive awareness raising and outreach activities to ensure that as many children as possible are accessing education.

The project aims to provide emergency alternative care for unaccompanied and separated IDP boys and girls. This care will be provided through community based support systems such as foster families, as well as emergency alternative shelter for children who cannot be placed with foster families. At the same time, the process of family tracing and reunification for separated and unaccompanied children will be started upon identification to ensure swift reunification or other suitable long-term solution.</narrative>
  </description>
